<p>Merlot displays a spectrum from deep ruby-garnet in youth to brick-tinged mahogany with age. Young Merlots from warm climates like Napa Valley exhibit an almost opaque purple-black core, indicating concentrated anthocyanins (color compounds). The wine's viscosity—visible as "legs" running down the glass—reflects its typically generous alcohol content of 13.5-15%, with premium examples showing excellent clarity and brilliance that speaks to careful winemaking.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Aromatic Complexity</h3>

<p>Merlot's aromatic profile unfolds in distinct layers. <strong>Primary fruit aromas</strong> center on dark berries—blackberry, black cherry, and plum—with warmer climates producing jammy, concentrated notes while cooler regions yield more restrained red fruit character. <strong>Secondary fermentation aromas</strong> contribute chocolate, coffee, and subtle vanilla from oak aging, particularly in Bordeaux-style expressions. <strong>Tertiary aging bouquet</strong> in mature bottles reveals leather, tobacco leaf, dried herbs, and forest floor earthiness—hallmarks of Pomerol's legendary Merlot-based wines.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Palate Structure and Mouthfeel</h3>

<p>Merlot's defining characteristic is its supple, velvety texture created by naturally lower tannin levels compared to Cabernet Sauvignon. The wine typically presents medium to full body with moderate acidity (6.0-6.5 pH), creating an approachable, rounded mouthfeel. Premium examples balance this softness with sufficient structure—think Château Pétrus's silky yet age-worthy profile.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Flavor Journey</h3>

<p>On the palate, Merlot delivers rich dark fruit flavors—blackberry compote, cherry liqueur, and dark plum—supported by warming spices like cinnamon, clove, and black pepper. Terroir-driven examples show distinct mineral qualities: graphite and wet stone from Right Bank Bordeaux, or dusty earth from Washington State. Oak integration adds layers of vanilla, cedar, and subtle smoke without overwhelming the fruit.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Finish and Quality Indicators</h3>

<p>Quality Merlots exhibit a long, satisfying finish lasting 30+ seconds, with flavors evolving from fruit to spice to earthy complexity. <strong>Premium markers</strong> include seamless oak integration, persistent aromatics that develop in the glass, balanced alcohol despite ripeness, and the ability to improve with 5-15 years of cellaring. The finish should feel complete and harmonious, never showing harsh tannins or alcohol heat.</p>

